<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-5991-34> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Micaceous pottery bowl by Bernadette Track, Taos Pueblo; ca. 2000\r\nPottery; 17,5 x 28 x 22 cm.\r\nRMV 5991-34; purchased by Pieter Hovens in 2002 at Tony Reyna’s, Taos Pueblo\r\n\r\nPottery made with clay containing naturally occurring mica was produced in northern New Mexico by Pueblo, Apache, and Navajo groups dating back to A.D. 1300. Pre-contact and Early Historic pottery vessels made of this material were almost exclusively used for cooking as micaceous clay has long been known for its ability to withstand thermal shock (Anderson 1999).\r\n\r\nPainted pottery wares in the American Southwest began making the transition from utility ware to fine art in the 1920s when scholars began encouraging potters to keep their great traditions alive (Bernstein 1994). Micaceous cooking wares lagged behind this transition until the early 1990s when artists working in this medium began elaborating and refining their pottery for sale on the art market.\r\n\r\nFinished micaceous clay vessels can be bright shiny gold if fired in an atmosphere rich in oxygen. If the fire is smothered the atmosphere is reduced resulting in shiny black vessels with silvery flecks of mica. This elegantly simple micaceous effigy bowl was coated with an enriched micaceous clay slip on both the interior and exterior. The female figure on the left rim has slightly open tool-impressed eyes, a rather flat nose, and tool impressed hair combed forward terminating at the forehead, and extending laterally where it is tied into buns on either side of the head.\r\n\r\nThe figure on the right has a flat nose, slightly oval mouth, closed slightly “U” shaped semicircular tool impressed eyes, and tool impressed hair swept back into a bun on the back of the head. Both figures have square shoulders that sweep outward like arms to form the rim and body of the vessel they share. Both figures appear to be singing. The lack of fire clouds (areas where the fuel comes into contact with the pot during firing) suggests that the vessel was fired in an electric kiln, an increasingly common practice.\r\n\r\nDuane Anderson\r\nMuseum of Indian Arts and Culture, Santa Fe, NM; 2013\r\n\r\n\r\nDuane Anderson, All That Glitters: The Emergence of Native American Micaceous Art Pottery in Northern New Mexico; SAR Press; Santa Fe, 1999. Bruce Bernstein, Potters and Patrons: The Creation of Pueblo Art Pottery; in: American Indian Art 20/1:70-79; 1994.\r\n\r\nTaos pottery\r\nTaos is known for its robust pottery with its characteristic fine shine, the result of using clay with tiny mica flecks who also act as temper. Their thick-walled bean pots, well suited for simmering beans and stews, were popular in other pueblos and Hispanic households.\r\n\r\nThe tourist trade had its impact on Taos since the early 20th century, and potters have produced miniature animals and bowls for this new market. The selfconscious and controlled development of Taos Pueblo as a tourist attraction after the Second World War has furthered potterymaking. Visitors can purchase Taos ceramics from a variety of small shops along the access road to the pueblo and around the central plaza. Whereas neighbouring Picuris potters have adhered to traditional clays and forms, Taos potters have been producing a whole range of forms, figures, colors and decorations since the 1980s, including non-micaceous clays (Hayes and Blom 1996:150-153).\r\n\r\nIn 1960 Taos was declared a National Historic Landmark and two years later the pueblo was recognized as a World Heritage Site by the UNESCO. In 1966 it was put on the U.S. Register of Historic Places.\r\n\r\nMany dances at Taos are open to the public. Animal dances take place during the end and beginning of the year. Foot races are organized on the feast days of Santa Cruz (May 3) and San Geronimo (September 30), and an annual powwow takes place during the second weekend of July.\r\nPieter Hovens; 2005\r\n\r\nTAOS Taos is bekend vanwege haar robuuste aardewerk met karakteristieke glans, het gevolg van het gebruik van micahoudende klei. De dikwandige potten, uiterst geschikt voor het langdurig sudderen van stoofpotten met bonen en vlees, waren populair in andere pueblos en de Spaanse buren.\r\n\r\nEvenals in Picuris begon men in Taos omstreeks de eeuwwisseling met de productie van dierfiguurtjes. Ook maakte men kleine potjes, dat alles voor toeristen.\r\n\r\nNa de Tweede Wereldoorlog pakte het bestuur van Taos de ontwikkeling van het toerisme professioneel aan en ontwikkelde een vorm van gecontroleerd toerisme waarbij bezoekers in staat werden gesteld om een deel van het dorp te bezoeken om daar Indiaans handwerk en etenswaren te kopen. Dat leidde ook tot een heropleving van de aardewerkproductie: deels dikwandige potten en kannen naar traditioneel voorbeeld, deels in stijlen (kleisoort, kleur, decoratie, motieven, vorm) ontleend aan andere pueblos. Dit aardewerk wordt verkocht in de winkeltjes langs de plaza, het dorpsplein, en langs de toegangsweg naar de pueblo.\r\n\r\nDe opbrengsten van het toerisme werden geïnvesteerd in de restauratie van de twee historische kernen van de pueblo, alsmede in de infrastructuur: wegen, scholen, studiebeurzen, gezondheidszorg, e.d. In 1960 werd Taos tot nationaal monument uitgeroepen en in 1962 erkende de UNESCO Taos pueblo als World Heritage Site." .
